  "method": "We propose Predictive Hierarchical KV (PHKV), a three-part caching system that keeps exact recent context, compresses the distant past into a small set of multi-aspect summary slots per chunk, and recalls exact keys/values on demand via a lightweight predictor and an ANN index. At runtime, the model holds a full-fidelity sliding window (e.g., last W tokens) in DRAM. Older tokens are grouped into fixed-size chunks; each chunk is replaced by k summary KV slots that approximate the chunk’s attention behavior. A tiny predictor, queried with the current query vector Q_t and cheap metadata, decides which summaries (and, when needed, which exact evicted tokens) to materialize for attention at this step. Evicted exact KV entries are quantized and parked off-DRAM together with an ANN index over their keys to enable fast recall when Q_t demands it.\n\nChunk compression is multi-view and hierarchical. For each aging chunk, we cluster or low-rank factorize its key matrix to produce k centroids that act like viewer tokens capturing different semantic aspects of the chunk; corresponding summary values are fitted (e.g., via attention-weighted regression) so that attending to these k slots approximates attending to the full chunk. As chunks age further, we pyramid-merge summaries across adjacent chunks (k -> k/2) to cap memory growth while preserving a coarse global signal. Summaries retain position encodings (e.g., via centroided rotary phases) so relative alignment is not lost, and all summaries and their small per-slot stats (token counts, last-hit time) remain resident; full KVs are evicted.\n\nEviction and recall are predictor-guided to save bandwidth. A small MLP or logistic head takes features such as dot-products between Q_t and each summary key, recency, usage, and entropy of past attentions to predict which summaries will receive nontrivial attention mass. Only predicted-relevant summaries are exposed to the attention kernel. If a chosen summary’s pre-softmax score crosses a threshold, we probe the off-DRAM ANN index with Q_t (or the summary key) to fetch the top-r exact KVs from the corresponding chunk and transiently splice them into the attention computation, replacing or augmenting the coarse slot. This prefetch is quantized and batched across layers to amortize I/O. A strict bandwidth budget governs how many exact KVs can be pulled per step; when exceeded, we fall back to the summaries (graceful degradation).\n\nTraining makes the model robust to partial and summarized caches and teaches the predictor what to keep. We fine-tune with KV-dropout that randomly replaces old chunks by their k-slot summaries (and zero-pads missing entries) to match target retention rates, so the decoder learns to operate when only summaries are present. In parallel, we generate pseudo-relevance labels for chunks: for a small subset of steps during fine-tuning, we measure the change in next-token loss when including vs excluding a chunk (or its exact top-r tokens) and train the predictor to classify chunks as helpful or not; simple cosine-similarity gates with Q_t serve as a cheap proxy feature during inference. Distillation from full-cache teacher runs can further shape the summary fitting and predictor thresholds. At deployment, PHKV delivers: exact KVs for the recent window; k-per-chunk summaries for the distant past; a predictor that minimizes unnecessary memory traffic; and an ANN-backed, on-the-fly recall path that restores fidelity only where the model would otherwise under-attend to distant but relevant tokens.",
  "rationale": "Long contexts overload DRAM with large KV caches and saturate bandwidth, yet uniformly truncating or naively compressing distant tokens harms the ability to retrieve far-away facts. PHKV cuts bandwidth by (a) pyramiding older tokens into a tiny number of multi-aspect summaries, so the attention kernel rarely touches large blocks of KVs, and (b) using a learned predictor to avoid moving data that will not affect the softmax—only when the model is likely to need specificity do we fetch a small set of exact KVs. This preserves recall for distant evidence because every chunk remains represented by semantically diverse keys, and exact tokens can be reinstated on demand within a strict bandwidth budget.\n\nRobustness comes from aligning training and inference: the model is explicitly exposed to partial/summarized caches and learns to treat missing tokens as zero-padded while relying on summaries, eliminating the distribution shift that typically degrades performance under cache thinning. Pseudo-relevance supervision and similarity-based gating provide a practical signal for what to keep, while the ANN index ensures that even if a useful token was evicted, it remains recoverable with low overhead. Together, these mechanisms maintain long-range attention quality while substantially reducing memory movement.",
