  "method": "Build a dual-scale memory for long-context decoding: (1) a recent-window cache that stores full-precision keys/values (K,V) for the last W tokens per head, and (2) a long-range bank organized into fixed-length segments (e.g., 512–2k tokens) where each segment holds a compact summary per head plus a small set of high-importance \"support\" tokens. At inference, attention over distant context first consults each segment’s summary prototypes; only if a prototype scores highly does the model optionally touch its associated support tokens. This keeps most memory bandwidth on the recent window and a tiny set of routed long-range entries.\n\nAttach a lightweight relevance selector that runs alongside decoding to assign keep scores to tokens and segments. The selector uses cheap features available at decode time (position, per-head key norms, a down-projected query·key score, cumulative attention so far, and topic/entity cues) to predict each token’s future utility. Periodically (e.g., at segment boundaries or every M tokens), perform an O(K) refinement pass over the candidate set to retain—using adjacent local swaps to bubble up the top-K tokens/segments—and evict the rest. Before eviction, roll evicted tokens into the segment summary using an uncertainty-gated exponential moving average: if the selector (or an auxiliary uncertainty head) is unsure the summary already captures a token, its contribution is up-weighted or the token is temporarily kept as a support exemplar.\n\nCompress long-range memory per head with a prototype low-rank representation. For keys, maintain a small dictionary of head-specific prototype directions (e.g., 16–64 per segment) and store each rolled-up token as a soft assignment to prototypes (or a quantized residual). For values, learn a head-specific projection to a low-dimensional subspace and accumulate summary coefficients there. Each segment thus provides: prototype keys, low-rank value coefficients, and a handful of support tokens (original K,V) for hard cases. At query time, attention first scores prototype keys; their weights linearly combine low-rank values to yield an approximate context vector. If the max prototype score or a confidence metric exceeds a threshold, the model optionally re-attends to the few linked support tokens to refine the result, amortizing bandwidth to rare, high-gain lookups.\n\nAllocate memory budgets and compression granularities per head, since some heads are dominantly local while others carry global signals. Learn these budgets with a sparsity-regularized allocation during distillation: train a student that uses the compressed/evicted memory against a teacher with a full cache, minimizing next-token loss and matching teacher attentions on sampled heads/layers, plus a reconstruction loss for prototype attention vs true attention over distant tokens. A mild group-sparsity penalty on per-head long-range usage encourages specialization and yields stable head-wise budgets. Deploy with infrequent maintenance steps (at segment boundaries) to bound CPU/GPU cache traffic; most tokens are written once then either summarized or dropped, and most long-range attention touches only prototypes, cutting both storage and memory bandwidth while preserving access to genuinely relevant distant content.",
  "rationale": "The approach reduces bandwidth by (a) sharply limiting how many distant tokens remain in full precision, (b) routing most long-range attention through tiny per-segment prototype summaries, and (c) performing eviction and summary updates only at coarse intervals. At the same time, it preserves the ability to use faraway context by keeping a small, relevance-scored set of support tokens and enabling a two-step retrieval: cheap prototype attention followed by selective refinement when the summary indicates a strong match.\n\nKey design choices make this practical: a learned lightweight selector avoids scanning all distant tokens at full cost; an O(K) adjacent-swap refinement pass maintains a high-quality top-K keep set without quadratic work; prototype-based, low-rank K/V summaries retain the principal long-range signals per head; uncertainty-gated EMA roll-ups prevent premature overcompression; and per-head budget specialization focuses capacity on the heads that actually exploit long-range cues. Distillation from a full-cache teacher aligns the compressed memory’s attentions and token predictions with the original model, yielding strong fidelity under tight memory budgets.",
